  <h2>What is Verlan?</h2>
  
  <p>Verlan is a form of French slang (<em>argot</em>) characterized by the reversal of syllables in standard French words. The term "verlan" itself is a perfect example of this mechanism—it derives from the French phrase "<em>l'envers</em>" meaning "the reverse" or "backwards." When you reverse the syllables of "l'en-ver" you get "ver-lan," creating a word that describes its own formation process.</p>

  <p>This linguistic phenomenon represents one of the most dynamic and creative aspects of contemporary French. Unlike traditional slang that merely substitutes one word for another, verlan transforms the very structure of words, creating a playful code that requires both linguistic awareness and cultural knowledge to decipher. For anyone seeking to understand modern French as it's actually spoken—particularly in urban environments, music, film, and youth culture—verlan is not merely optional knowledge but an essential component of authentic French comprehension.</p>

  <h2>The Basic Mechanism</h2>

  <p>At its core, verlan operates through syllable inversion. A standard French word is divided into its constituent syllables, and these are then reversed in order. However, the process is not always mathematically precise and has evolved to include several variations and exceptions that have become standardized through usage.</p>

  <p>Consider the classic example: the French word "<em>femme</em>" (woman) becomes "<em>meuf</em>" in verlan. The word divides into "fe-mme," and when reversed becomes "mme-fe." Through phonological naturalization, this becomes "meuf" (pronounced roughly like "muff" in English). Similarly, "<em>lourd</em>" (heavy/boring) transforms into "<em>relou</em>"—a term that has become so mainstream it's regularly heard in everyday conversation across France.</p>

